	therapeutic use; Antihypertensive Agents, therapeutic use; Blood
	Pressure; Blood Pressure Determination; Blood Pressure Monitors;
	Calcium Channel Blockers, therapeutic use; Cardiovascular Diseases,
	epidemiology/prevention /&/ control; Diagnostic Tests, Routine; Diuretics,
	therapeutic use; Humans; Hypertension, diagnosis/prevention /&/ control/therapy;
	Receptors, Angiotensin, antagonists /&/ inhibitors; Risk Factors;
	Risk Reduction Behavior; Vasodilator Agents, therapeutic use},
  medline-pst = {ppublish},
  owner = {grissu},
  pmid = {12748199},
  review = {Hypertensive Urgencies and Emergencies.
	
	Patients with marked BP elevations and acute target-organ damage
	
	(eg, encephalopathy, myocardial infarction, unstable angina, pulmonary
	
	edema, eclampsia, stroke, head trauma, life-threatening arterial bleeding,
	or aortic
	
	dissection) require hospitalization and parenteral drug therapy.1
